description: Trend Watch 👀: Stealth wealth (or quiet luxury), a phrase usually meant to identify fashion, is a trend that puts more anonymity on your status. Like in the show, Succession, rather than subscribing to logo mania and labels, you pay attention to the smaller details that make you look more "put together." On a bigger scale, stealth wealth is being quiet about your wealth – much harder to emulate because today's internet pushes more people to exude wealth rather than keep it low key. Context: if your business model requires you to talk about financial milestones, it will be much harder. For example, course creators usually celebrate 7-figure milestones in their marketing; affiliate marketers usually take screenshots of monthly earnings to attract more business. I fall in this category of marketing financial milestones as that's what I help people achieve with their businesses. Although I've been relatively lowkey with it than other more successful course creators, I notice that the bigger and louder the numbers, the more clients they attract. The end goal for me is to build my business and diversify enough so that I eventually can take myself offline and earn more passively. Maybe you hear from me once every 6 months. 😂 One day, it will be my last post, but that day is not today. 😄 Not yet. #stealthwealth #stealthwealthaesthetic #quietluxury #succession #successionhbo

accumulated_text: Delvaux est une marque prestigieuse Belge et leur maroquinerie peut aisément rivaliser avec Hermès à mon sens toutes les mamans en flandres ont un delvaux Le pb avec Delvaux c’est que leurs sacs perdent de leur valeur alors que Hermès gagne de la valeur avec le temps;donc pas un investissement Haaa en tant que belge, je confirme, Delvaux = Hermès 🥰 Jamais j’échangerai mon Hermes contre un Delvaux 🙈 Beaucoup plus beau qu’un birkin vraiment Il n’est pas rare que les maisons de Luxe se fournissent de cuir issu de l’industrie alimentaire, il n’y a pas que Delvaux! C’est ce que même toutes les maisons de luxe font… Delvaux le premier sac que j'ai offert à ma mère 😁 les boutiques on disparu au fur et a mesure en Belgique c'est bien triste Le sac de luxe en Belgique 👌 on peut savoir les prix approximativement quoi? merci Et dire qu’ici au Congo 🇨🇩 précisément à Kinshasa Delvaux est un quartier 😅 je ne savais même pas que c’était une maison de marque wow!! Les vrais connaissent Do we need to have an appointment before ? Delvaux si on parle de qualité, elle dépasse toute les autres marques merdique ! Je connais Delvaux C’est moi nom de famille ✌🏻✌🏻 En france déjà le cuir vient obligatoirement de la chaîne alimentaire puisqu’il est interdit d’abattre ces animaux uniquement pour ça .. comment ça breveté le sac à main ? Il sont aussi dur à acheter que les sac hermes ? J’ai été maroquinier pour cette marque, ça reste du travail à la chaîne mais avec des pratiques artisanales. Sobre chic et élégant En Belgique, tout le monde a des Delvaux bien sûr j'ai un Delvaux😅😅😅😅😅😅💕💕💕💕💕💕 Quand je bossais pour Hermes on m’a toujours dit que tous les cuirs français viennent de l’industrie alimentaire. J’ai des bagages Delvaux avion (toile + cadre magnésium) de mes parents qui datent de 1951 Le cadeau de mes 30 ans je le porte encore tellement souvent Fabuleuse marques et d’une élégance extraordinaire ❤️❤️❤️ C’est mon rêve d’avoir un Delvaux ! description: The True Cost Of Quiet Luxury ~ Fast fashion is notorious for worker exploitation within the fashion supply chain, but there are countless examples of luxury brands using the same harmful labour practices. This is why we must shift the dial from solely critiquing fast fashion and instead focus on ~Big Fashion~  According to Bloomberg’s unmissable report into Loro Piana, the brand has done next to nothing for the indigenous community whose skilled labour they have relied on for the past 30 years. In fact, 80% of the community feel that they have not been fairly compensated.  We must continue to organise in solidarity with workers and their unions in a bid to create a fashion system that benefits everybody in the supply chain, irrespective of how ‘luxury’ a brand’s reputation is.   Resources:  The Vicuñas And The $9,000 Sweater [Bloomberg] The Brutal Cost of Quiet Luxury [Bloomberg YouTube] Fashion AccountabilityReport 2024 [Remake] #LoroPiana #QuietLuxury #Capitalism #LuxuryFashion #SustainableFashion #Sustainability #Billionaires

1. Quiet Luxury Quiet luxury is a trend that emphasizes understated elegance and high-quality materials without flashy logos or overly bold statements.  2.Statement Tiles Statement tiles are the way to go. They’re like art for your floors and walls, and they can really show off your personality. Whether you go for vibrant colors, intricate patterns, or something a bit more subtle, statement tiles can completely transform a room. 3.Midimalism If minimalism feels too stark and impersonal, and maximalism feels too loud and crazy for you, then midimalismmight be just what you need. 4. Round-Shaped Furniture: Softening the Edges Round furniture is a great way to break up all those straight lines and angles in your home. It adds a touch of playfulness and can make your space feel more dynamic and interesting. Plus, it’s super versatile and works well with a variety of design styles. 5.Thrifting Vintage Pieces: Sustainability Meets Style Thrifting is not only budget-friendly, but it’s also a great way to find unique, one-of-a-kind pieces that tell a story. Plus, it’s super sustainable, which is always a win in our book. #interiordesign #interiordecor #architecture#2025interiortrends #luxury #home#decor

description: Collecting old money lovers 180 People 👑✨ The British old money lifestyle is a unique tapestry woven from threads of history, tradition, and refined luxury. 🌍 In this world, wealth is a symbol of legacy and heritage, passed down through generations with a deep respect for tradition and an unwavering commitment to maintaining the family’s standing. 🏰 This lifestyle is characterized by grand country estates, bespoke fashion, and an appreciation for the finer things in life. 🌟 British old money families often reside in stately homes and country manors that have been in the family for centuries. 🏛️ These residences, whether in the rolling hills of the English countryside or in historic neighborhoods of London, are not just homes but embodiments of family history and cultural heritage. 🌿 Each room tells a story, adorned with heirlooms, antique furniture, and priceless art collections that reflect the family's taste and refinement. 🖼️🏺 Education is a cornerstone of the British old money lifestyle. 🎓 Children from these families are groomed from a young age to take on leadership roles and are often sent to prestigious schools and universities. Institutions such as Eton, Harrow, Oxford, and Cambridge are common choices, providing not only a world-class education but also a network of influential peers. 📚 These schools instill a sense of tradition, responsibility, and excellence that is crucial for maintaining the family's social and economic standing. 🏫 Luxury in the British old money lifestyle is synonymous with quality and craftsmanship. 👜👗 Old money families favor bespoke fashion and accessories, tailored by the world's finest artisans. Savile Row for tailored suits, Turnbull & Asser for shirts, and John Lobb for shoes are preferred not for their logos, but for their timeless elegance and superior craftsmanship. ✨ Each piece of clothing is a testament to the wearer’s appreciation for tradition and quality. 🧥👞 Automobiles are another symbol of the British old money lifestyle. 🚗 Classic cars such as vintage Rolls-Royces, Bentleys, and Aston Martins are prized possessions, often handed down through generation. 🇬🇧 #oldmoney#oldmoneyaesthetic#luxury#rich✨✨

description: Collecting old money lovers 932 People 👑✨ The British old money lifestyle is a unique tapestry woven from threads of history, tradition, and refined luxury. 🌍 In this world, wealth is a symbol of legacy and heritage, passed down through generations with a deep respect for tradition and an unwavering commitment to maintaining the family’s standing. 🏰 This lifestyle is characterized by grand country estates, bespoke fashion, and an appreciation for the finer things in life. 🌟 British old money families often reside in stately homes and country manors that have been in the family for centuries. 🏛️ These residences, whether in the rolling hills of the English countryside or in historic neighborhoods of London, are not just homes but embodiments of family history and cultural heritage. 🌿 Each room tells a story, adorned with heirlooms, antique furniture, and priceless art collections that reflect the family's taste and refinement. 🖼️🏺 Education is a cornerstone of the British old money lifestyle. 🎓 Children from these families are groomed from a young age to take on leadership roles and are often sent to prestigious schools and universities. Institutions such as Eton, Harrow, Oxford, and Cambridge are common choices, providing not only a world-class education but also a network of influential peers. 📚 These schools instill a sense of tradition, responsibility, and excellence that is crucial for maintaining the family's social and economic standing. 🏫 Luxury in the British old money lifestyle is synonymous with quality and craftsmanship. 👜👗 Old money families favor bespoke fashion and accessories, tailored by the world's finest artisans. Savile Row for tailored suits, Turnbull & Asser for shirts, and John Lobb for shoes are preferred not for their logos, but for their timeless elegance and superior craftsmanship. ✨ Each piece of clothing is a testament to the wearer’s appreciation for tradition and quality. 🧥👞 Automobiles are another symbol of the British old money lifestyle. 🚗 Classic cars such as vintage Rolls-Royces, Bentleys, and Aston Martins are prized possessions, often handed down through generation. 🇬🇧 #oldmoney#oldmoneyaesthetic#luxury#rich✨✨
